{
  "Stoichiometry uses balanced equations to calculate:": "",
  "Bond angles": "",
  "Atomic numbers": "",
  "Electron configurations": "",
  "Amounts of reactants and products": "",
  "Stoichiometry is the quantitative study of reactants and products in a chemical reaction, using mole ratios from the balanced equation.": "",
  "The coefficients in a balanced equation represent:": "",
  "Mass ratios": "",
  "Volume ratios only": "",
  "Mole ratios of reactants and products": "",
  "Charge ratios": "",
  "Coefficients give the mole ratios. In 2H₂ + O₂ → 2H₂O, the ratio is 2 mol H₂ : 1 mol O₂ : 2 mol H₂O.": "",
  "In 2H₂ + O₂ → 2H₂O, the mole ratio of H₂ to H₂O is:": "",
  "1:2": "",
  "2:1": "",
  "2:2 is not the same as 1:1": "",
  "1:1 (which is 2:2 simplified)": "",
  "Both coefficients are 2: 2 mol H₂ produces 2 mol H₂O. The simplified ratio is 1:1.": "",
  "The first step in any stoichiometry problem is:": "",
  "Write and balance the chemical equation": "",
  "Find the atomic number": "",
  "Measure the temperature": "",
  "Convert to liters": "",
  "Without a balanced equation, you don't have correct mole ratios — and all stoichiometric calculations depend on them.": "",
  "In 4Al + 3O₂ → 2Al₂O₃, if 4 mol Al reacts, how many moles of Al₂O₃ form?": "",
  "1 mol": "",
  "4 mol": "",
  "2 mol": "",
  "3 mol": "",
  "Mole ratio of Al to Al₂O₃ = 4:2. 4 mol Al × (2 mol Al₂O₃ / 4 mol Al) = 2 mol Al₂O₃.": "",
  "Mole-to-mole conversions use:": "",
  "Coefficients from the balanced equation (mole ratios)": "",
  "Molar masses to directly convert between substances": "",
  "Atomic numbers from the periodic table of elements": "",
  "Avogadro’s number (6.022 × 10²³ particles/mol)": "",
  "The mole ratio converts moles of one substance to moles of another. Molar mass converts moles to grams — a separate step.": "",
  "Gram-to-gram conversions require:": "",
  "No conversion needed; grams of one substance equal grams of another directly": "",
  "Direct division of masses using the ratio of molecular weights only": "",
  "Converting to moles first, using the mole ratio, then converting back to grams": "",
  "Adding masses of reactants together to determine total product mass": "",
  "Three-step process: grams → moles (÷ molar mass) → mole ratio → moles → grams (× molar mass).": "",
  "What is the 4-step stoichiometry method?": "",
  "Observe → hypothesize → test → conclude": "",
  "Balance equation → convert to moles → use mole ratio → convert to desired unit": "",
  "Filter → distill → crystallize → dry": "",
  "Weigh → measure → heat → cool": "",
  "Step 1: Balance. Step 2: Convert given quantity to moles. Step 3: Apply mole ratio. Step 4: Convert to requested unit.": "",
  "At STP, volume-to-volume conversions for gases are simplified because:": "",
  "Pressure is always zero": "",
  "All gases have the same mass": "",
  "Mole ratios equal volume ratios for gases at STP": "",
  "Temperature doesn't matter": "",
  "At STP, 1 mol of any gas = 22.4 L. So the coefficient ratio directly equals the volume ratio (Avogadro's law).": "",
  "Why must an equation be balanced before doing stoichiometry?": "",
  "Unbalanced equations give wrong mole ratios, violating conservation of mass": "",
  "It makes the equation look nicer": "",
  "Only for gas-phase reactions": "",
  "Balancing is optional": "",
  "The law of conservation of mass requires equal atoms on both sides. Incorrect coefficients would produce incorrect calculations.": "",
  "Define 'stoichiometry.'": "",
  "The measurement of reaction speed and how quickly reactants are consumed and products are formed over time": "",
  "The calculation of quantities (moles, grams, liters) in chemical reactions using mole ratios from balanced equations": "",
  "The arrangement of electrons in orbitals around the nucleus and their quantum mechanical energy levels": "",
  "The study of atomic structure, including protons, neutrons, and electrons that make up all elements": "",
  "From Greek 'stoicheion' (element) + 'metron' (measure). It lets you predict how much product you get from a given amount of reactant.": "",
  "Define 'mole ratio.'": "",
  "The ratio of moles of one substance to another, derived from the coefficients of a balanced equation": "",
  "The number of atoms in a mole, defined by Avogadro’s constant as 6.022 × 10²³ particles per mole": "",
  "The mass of one mole of a substance in grams, numerically equal to its atomic or molecular weight": "",
  "The ratio of protons to neutrons in the nucleus of an atom, which determines isotopic stability": "",
  "In 2H₂ + O₂ → 2H₂O, the mole ratio of H₂:O₂ is 2:1 and H₂:H₂O is 2:2 (or 1:1).": "",
  "What is a 'mass-to-mass problem'?": "",
  "A problem where you're given grams of one substance and asked to find grams of another, going through moles": "",
  "A problem using only Avogadro’s number to convert between particles and moles without mass calculations": "",
  "Weighing an object twice on different scales and comparing the two mass readings for accuracy": "",
  "Comparing the density of two substances to determine which one is heavier per unit volume": "",
  "Mass-to-mass: given grams → ÷ molar mass → moles → mole ratio → moles of target → × molar mass → grams of target.": "",
  "What does 'dimensional analysis' mean in stoichiometry?": "",
  "Drawing 3D molecular models": "",
  "Measuring the dimensions of a container": "",
  "Calculating electron orbitals": "",
  "Using conversion factors to cancel units step by step: grams → moles → moles → grams": "",
  "Dimensional analysis tracks units through the calculation, ensuring proper conversion. Units must cancel correctly at each step.": "",
  "What does 'balanced equation coefficients' provide for stoichiometry?": "",
  "The color of products": "",
  "The temperature of the reaction": "",
  "The mole ratios needed to convert between different substances in the reaction": "",
  "The atomic mass of each element": "",
  "Coefficients are the whole numbers in front of formulas. They establish the mole-to-mole relationships that are the backbone of stoichiometry.": "",
  "What does 'conversion factor' mean in stoichiometric calculations?": "",
  "The equilibrium constant (K) that describes the balance between products and reactants": "",
  "A ratio (like molar mass or mole ratio) used to convert between different units or substances": "",
  "The rate constant of a reaction that determines how fast the chemical process occurs": "",
  "The acceleration due to gravity (9.8 m/s²) used when calculating the weight of samples": "",
  "Common conversion factors in stoichiometry: molar mass (g/mol), Avogadro's number (particles/mol), and molar volume (22.4 L/mol at STP).": "",
  "In stoichiometry, what does 'given quantity' refer to?": "",
  "The theoretical yield of the product calculated from the equation": "",
  "The amount of substance you start with (provided in the problem)": "",
  "The molar mass of the substance in grams per mole from the table": "",
  "Avogadro’s number (6.022 × 10²³) that converts moles to particles": "",
  "The given quantity is your starting point — it could be grams, moles, liters, or particles of one substance.": "",
  "What does 'desired quantity' mean?": "",
  "The amount of substance you're trying to find (the answer the problem asks for)": "",
  "The limiting reagent that is completely consumed first during the reaction": "",
  "The catalyst that speeds up the reaction without being consumed in it": "",
  "The excess reagent that remains unreacted after the reaction has completed": "",
  "You map from given → moles → mole ratio → moles of target → desired quantity (in whatever unit is requested).": "",
  "What is a 'mole-to-mole problem'?": "",
  "A problem involving only masses": "",
  "A problem about Avogadro's number": "",
  "A problem with no conversion needed": "",
  "A problem where both given and desired quantities are in moles, requiring only the mole ratio": "",
  "Mole-to-mole is the simplest stoichiometry type: given moles of A × (coefficient B ÷ coefficient A) = moles of B.": "",
  "What does 'stoichiometric coefficient' mean?": "",
  "The charge on an ion in an ionic compound, indicating the number of electrons gained or lost by the atom": "",
  "The atomic number of an element, which represents the total number of protons found in the nucleus": "",
  "The number placed before a formula in a balanced equation, representing the relative moles of that substance": "",
  "The subscript in a chemical formula, which indicates the number of atoms of each element per molecule": "",
  "Coefficients and subscripts are different. Coefficients (before the formula) represent moles; subscripts (within the formula) represent atoms per molecule.": "",
  "How many grams of H₂O form when 4 g of H₂ reacts with excess O₂? (2H₂ + O₂ → 2H₂O, H₂ = 2 g/mol, H₂O = 18 g/mol)": "",
  "4 g": "",
  "72 g": "",
  "18 g": "",
  "36 g": "",
  "4 g H₂ ÷ 2 g/mol = 2 mol H₂. Ratio 2:2 → 2 mol H₂O. 2 × 18 = 36 g H₂O.": "",
  "In the Haber process N₂ + 3H₂ → 2NH₃, how many moles of NH₃ form from 6 mol H₂?": "",
  "6 mol": "",
  "6 mol H₂ × (2 mol NH₃ / 3 mol H₂) = 4 mol NH₃.": "",
  "A student burns 12 g of carbon in excess oxygen: C + O₂ → CO₂. How many grams of CO₂ form? (C = 12 g/mol, CO₂ = 44 g/mol)": "",
  "12 g": "",
  "88 g": "",
  "32 g": "",
  "44 g": "",
  "12 g C ÷ 12 = 1 mol C. 1:1 ratio → 1 mol CO₂. 1 × 44 = 44 g CO₂.": "",
  "For the reaction 2NaOH + H₂SO₄ → Na₂SO₄ + 2H₂O, how many moles of NaOH are needed to react with 0.5 mol H₂SO₄?": "",
  "0.25 mol": "",
  "0.5 mol": "",
  "0.5 mol H₂SO₄ × (2 mol NaOH / 1 mol H₂SO₄) = 1 mol NaOH.": "",
  "How many liters of O₂ at STP are needed to completely combust 2 mol CH₄? (CH₄ + 2O₂ → CO₂ + 2H₂O)": "",
  "22.4 L": "",
  "89.6 L": "",
  "44.8 L": "",
  "67.2 L": "",
  "2 mol CH₄ × (2 mol O₂ / 1 mol CH₄) = 4 mol O₂. 4 × 22.4 L = 89.6 L at STP.": "",
  "A pharmacist needs to produce 50 g of aspirin (C₉H₈O₄, 180 g/mol). How many moles are needed?": "",
  "0.278 mol": "",
  "50 mol": "",
  "180 mol": "",
  "50 g ÷ 180 g/mol = 0.278 mol. This is a grams-to-moles conversion — the first step in planning a synthesis.": "",
  "In 2Fe₂O₃ + 3C → 4Fe + 3CO₂, if 320 g of Fe₂O₃ (160 g/mol) reacts, how many grams of Fe (56 g/mol) form?": "",
  "56 g": "",
  "224 g": "",
  "448 g": "",
  "112 g": "",
  "320÷160 = 2 mol Fe₂O₃. 2 × (4/2) = 4 mol Fe. 4 × 56 = 224 g Fe.": "",
  "A car engine burns octane: 2C₈H₁₈ + 25O₂ → 16CO₂ + 18H₂O. What is the mole ratio of octane to CO₂?": "",
  "2:16 or 1:8": "",
  "2:25 or 1:12.5": "",
  "1:1 (equal ratio)": "",
  "8:1 (inverse ratio)": "",
  "From the coefficients: 2 mol C₈H₁₈ : 16 mol CO₂, which simplifies to 1:8. Each mole of octane produces 8 moles of CO₂.": "",
  "How many grams of NaCl form when 80 g of NaOH (40 g/mol) reacts with excess HCl? (NaOH + HCl → NaCl + H₂O, NaCl = 58.5 g/mol)": "",
  "117 g": "",
  "80 g": "",
  "58.5 g": "",
  "234 g": "",
  "80÷40 = 2 mol NaOH. 1:1 ratio → 2 mol NaCl. 2 × 58.5 = 117 g NaCl.": "",
  "An antacid tablet contains 0.5 g of CaCO₃ (100 g/mol). It reacts with stomach acid: CaCO₃ + 2HCl → CaCl₂ + H₂O + CO₂. How many moles of HCl can it neutralize?": "",
  "0.01 mol": "",
  "0.05 mol": "",
  "0.005 mol": "",
  "0.5 g ÷ 100 = 0.005 mol CaCO₃. Ratio 1:2 → 0.005 × 2 = 0.01 mol HCl neutralized.": ""
